The archive is composed of collections related to the GLBT experience both on-campus and in the surrounding community. The GLBT Archive has been increasingly used for research, organizations, and courses throughout the campus and community prompting our need to process and arrange the collection and develop a complete finding aid that will be available digitally and, ultimately, to digitize the Archive.\n\nThe desired student employee would have an academic or personal interest in the materials.  Archive, processing or library work experience is desired but not required.  This is an excellent opportunity for a student with an interest in Information Sciences, History, Sociology, Anthropology, Academic Administration, or related fields.   \n\nThe employee is expected to begin in January 2014 and will work approximately 20 hours per week for the Spring Semester 2014.  The position has the possibility for continuation beyond the Spring 2014 semester if the project is progressing sufficiently.  Cushing Library is a security sensitive workplace and therefore all employees are required to submit to a background check.\nApplicants should send a resume with cover letter explaining their interest in this particular project to the project coordinator, Michael Jackson.  Application packets may be submitted to Mr. Jackson by e-mail, mgj@library.tamu.edu , or may be delivered in person to the reception desk at the Cushing Library during normal operating hours (M-F 8 am \u2013 6 pm).  \nPlease submit applications before Wednesday, December 11, 2013.  \n\nSuitable applicants will be contacted as soon as possible to schedule interviews. I know that is a particularly problematic statement that gets made in the media and in some LGBT circles, but that is not what this is about. Here is more information about this film:\n\n\"The New Black is a documentary that tells the story of how the African-American community is grappling with the gay rights issue in light of the recent gay marriage movement and the fight over civil rights. The film documents activists, families and clergy on both sides of the campaign to legalize gay marriage and examines homophobia in the black community\u2019s institutional pillar \u2013 the black church \u2013 and reveals the Christian right wing\u2019s strategy of exploiting this phenomenon in order to pursue an anti-gay political agenda.\n\nThe New Black takes viewers into the pews and onto the streets and provides a seat at the kitchen table as it tells the story of the historic fight to win marriage equality in Maryland and charts the evolution of this divisive issue within the black community.\"", "id": "10151674109966198_27385945", "user_likes": false}]}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/34429236197/posts/10151674109966198", "name": "Comment"}, {"link": "https://www.facebook.com/34429236197/posts/10151674109966198", "name": "Like"}], "updated_time": "2013-11-05T16:13:11+0000", "caption": "scontent-a-dfw.xx.fbcdn.net", "link": "https://scontent-a-dfw.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-prn2/q71/1377305_10151647405891198_1188730984_n.jpg", "likes": {"paging": {"cursors": {"after": "MTY2Njg0MjIxMQ==", "before": "MTY2Njg0MjIxMQ=="}}, "data": [{"id": "1666842211", "name": "Mark Gardner"}]}, "created_time": "2013-11-05T01:44:03+0000", "message": "Don't forget about the exclusive showing of the documentary \"The New Black\", showing tomorrow evening at 7pm in ILSB Auditorium.
